15s trial cuz changed sound file after this
15s trial cuz changed sound file after this
15s trial snake already facing away from speaker. 15s trial cuz changed sound file after this
30s trial from here on out.
definite hiss half-way through the trial. Assumed defensive posture by pulling whole body behind head. Also dropped lower jaw!
hissed when putting into hutch
hissed 3 times!
snake dropped lower jaw at Chris after trial. Not happy; Clear retreat behaviour 2/3rds into the trial. Snake has heavy blueing for a shed today.
moderate blueing of the eye for shed
reversing movement whole time (ie, not in direction of head).
hissed three times.
basically went straight out of grid without delay.
head jerks were toward the speaker
the 1cm movement of head was back toward body (so reverse direction).
the 5cm toward the speaker was simply moving angle of the head
the 15cm toward-speaker measurement was a reverse movement for a coil. hissed twice. Dropped lower jaw. For whole trial, maintained defensive posture that he had from the start of the trial.
rate of tongue flicking a few sec into the trial. Chris and Christina said defo seemed to respond to the sound.
Was trying to climb the wall of hutch prior to lifting hutch.
the 2 tongue flicks were right at the start, then none after that. Was trying to climb the wall of hutch prior to lifting hutch.
she held her initial position the whole time, which was slightly raised whole time.
two tongue flicks were at the first few sec of trial, then none rest of trial. Maintained same body position whole time.
Really interesting behaviour: defensive retreat for most of the trial: head maintained same position but body reversing, gathering coils behind head. Like facing an enemy. Also hissed three times.
very different from last sound trial. Normal, non-angry, cruising behaviour. Vs angry and defensive behaviour at sound in last trial!
1 tongue flick at start of trial, then 1 just after trial ended.
seemed to have gone asleep. Haha
hissed once, sort of mid-way through trial.
heavy blueing of the eyes today for a shed.
three hisses.
head slightly raised off ground whole trial.
mistrial b/c head under body when lifted body.
1 hiss. Dropped lower jaw. Coiled behind head and stayed there thereafter.
moderate blueing of the eye for shed
head eventually turned around to face speaker.
that 1 freeze-behaviour was right when the sound started, ie. in response to the sound starting.
this head-flicking behaviour seems to be how he's choosing to move atm. But we're calling it head-flicks and are doing so for every trial for him, obviously regardless of trial type.
stopped tongue-flicking immediately when the sound started.
defensive gathering of coils behind head and kept head rised, ready for a strike. Hissed twice. Also dropped lower jaw slightly.
4 hisses.
we think he fell asleep.
initially, cautionary exploratory, before started to travel. Interesting raising of head (periscoping to get better view of surroundings) into the air on two occasions: 10cm then 30cm next time.
heavy blueing of the eyes today for a shed.
6cm periscoping of head (looking at the box above her slightly swaying back and forth)
she brought the back end of her body closer to her, but head stayed same position.
froze at very end of trial when got closest to the speaker, and stopped flicking tongue at that very moment too.
periscoped about 6cm on two occasions.
did not move a muscle the whole time. Alert, but choosing not to move.
boring!
absolutely no behaviour to record. Sat there like a dead snake.
very interesting response. Like he was trying to work out where the sound was coming from, and then when he faced the speaker, he kept his direction and head in the same spot. Fixation at 26sec

as soon as sound was gone, he changed direction. He maintained his head direction facing the sound source whilst moving perpendicular to the sound. Keeping eye on threat source but move away: typical taipan behaviour.
at start of trial, moved back half of body inward, toward the rest of her body.
moderate blueing of the eye for shed

all head jerks were small. Not normal for this snake this movement. Unusual for this snake. Like he was fixated on the ground. Lots of short tongue flicks scenting the ground. Possibly scenting where his own body just was?
all distance moved was in reverse, ie. not forward of the head. Like a swivel.
right when sound started, she moved 1cm in direction of head.
one big hissed. Dropped lower jaw. Immediately once sound started, he retracted head backwards toward body. Like in response to sound.
skipped cuz AEC lady here and snake is stroke-like.
redo b/c couldn't see tongue flicks
just when trial ended, did one small head-jerk.
skipped cuz AEC lady here and snake is blue.
a very interesting one! Right when sound started, he pulled his head back rapidly. Thereafter it was cautious and tense behaviour.
copied row here from above b/c skipped earlier today. Head jerk was when he touched himself. This snake is a bit special. Possibly had a stroke a few months back.
copied row here from above b/c skipped earlier today. Whilst head did not move, back half of body moved to left about 20cm. Not in coiling-toward-body fashion though.
copied row here from above b/c skipped earlier today.

shifted direction of head slightly when the sound started. Important: Started trial in a defensive posture (tension in the body, slightly coiled backward) and maintained that exact position the whole trial.
Ugrgrade actually made it through a trial!
3 hisses.
lots of little head-jerks nearly whole time during the trial.
he stopped moving right when the sound stopped, so like a reaction to a difference in the sound.
once settled into position, she kept her position whole time, with head raised about 5cm.
seemed to be fixated on a patch of the ground.
heavy blueing of the eyes today for a shed.
heavy blueing of the eyes today for a shed.
a few seconds into the trial, she moved the back half of her body about 5cm closer toward the head.
in response to sound, head turned directly toward the speaker. Within trial, for a portion, he kept his head stationary and repositioned body. So defensive fixation behaviour.
didn't seem to take note of sound. Also, already moving forward when the sound started.
the one tongue flick was right at the start of the trial, then none.

heavy blueing of the eyes today for a shed. Fixation behaviour at end of trial: head facing sound while gathering tail around to behind the body. Lasted 3-4s though, so not as long as Fibby has done when I've called it fixation behaviour.
pivotted at the head and moved the front half of his body around his head. Chris thinks doesn't classify as fixation behaviour. I agree.
started to move a few seconds at end of trial and continued to move after trial- increasingly once commotion in room from ending trial.
angled head up at one stage briefly, and also down at one stage briefly. The 3 head jerks were subtle, but Chris says they are head jerks.
low level blueing of eyes. About to shed very soon.
whole time seemed focused on getting his body sorted. Retarded mover. Somewhat knotted himself and had loops he had to work to the back of his body.
Body moved more than head: pulled back of body a bit closer to body.
bit of movement just at the end.

also about 5cm periscoping of head too (2/3rd through the trial). Note with the head-jerking behaviour: the only other time we notice him doing this is when Chris approaches him. So Chris says defo a defensive behaviour.
started trial with head raised and maintained that position for duration of trial.
she turned toward the speaker and in about 6sec then decided to progress directly toward it, though cautiously (slowly). Moving slowly directly toward the sub.
moved back half of body twice, once each after slight movement of head forward. So, like he was thinking of going somewhere and then didn't.
1 hiss. Fixation on us at the end, whereby he kept facing us and pulled head back slightly and moved first 1/3 of his body. I think he did this on another trial too.
took a while to get moving, but once decided to go, went and continued.
1 hiss (toward end of trial). He also pulled his body a bit closer together at that point, with head staying still. At that point, pulled the tail closer to the body by about 5cm.
Played at 87dB. snake gathered coils and then sat there (asleep probs) for rest of trial.
Played at 87dB. just the head moved (side to side), not the body.
Played at 87dB. maintained head position slightly lifted off the ground for whole trial, which is how she came out of the hutch b/c was trying to scale the inside of the box when lifted it.
Played at 87dB. stopped head movement exactly when sound started. Fixation behaviour twice (head raised and alert and static, whilst gathered some coils: at start and at end.
Played at 87dB.
Played at 87dB.
lots of little head-jerks nearly whole time during the trial.
1 hiss 2/3rds through trial. Kept initial defensive pose for whole trial.
Played at 87dB.
moved tail ~5cm toward his body.
just shed this morn, so eyes clear now. Head-jerk straight away when sound started.
little tail readjustment 2cm about 20s into trial.
says side 1 on box but actually side 2
she lifted her head briefly and about 1cm aboutu half way through her movement forward.
when moved head back 1cm, her tail was pulled in about 2cm as well. Otherwise no movement.
light blueing of eyes. About to shed
head was slightly raised off ground about 8cm at start of trial and kept it there, motionless the whole time.
periscoped about 6cm on one occasion.
came out with head up about 20cm and kept it up the whole trial.
pulled tail in a bit too when moved head. Also, started trial with head coiled back ready to strike and kept that position whole trial.
eyes now clear cuz about to shed.
moved head super slowly toward the sound.
freeze behaviour b/c when stopped it was not in natural sitting position, unlike all other times when a death adder stopped.

took off left in response to hutch being lifted, then pulled a 90 degree turn toward sub and maintained that heading for rest of trial. Like someone shaking a rat over the sub, Chris says. Like why change behaviour so suddenly and completely without a stimulus?
kept slightly raised (5cm head position the whole time).
moved tail inward when stopped, so not freeze behaviour.
slight movement of tail inward toward body.
had head raised~10cm when hutch removed, and kept it there whole time. Slightly moved head 1cm toward speaker.
stayed in alert posture (head slightly raised) whole time. Same posture whole time.
changed direction to head toward the speaker. Spent some time to check it out.
started heading way, then changed direction to head toward the speaker.
just the head slightly moved
just before this trial, we accidentally played sound from side 2, so re-trial straight away after reset.
moved head to the point where whole body was in horseshoe shape.
Eyes fully clear cuz shed yesterday morning before day of trials began. Back of body moving slightly toward head prior to sound and stopped exactly on cue when sound started. Coincidence? Who knows.
stopped forward movement on cue when sound stopped.
we think he may have fallen asleep.
Mistrial b/c I narrated the trial for a Science Vs. podcast (quietly though so I'd say usable data, actually. Dropped lower jaw just before trial after the snake hutch was removed.
storms yesterday, so death adders may be sensing that and moving more as a result.
tail sitting on top of head whole time. Ambush position
on the move. Started moving prior to sound starting.
prior to sound, 1 hiss in response to box being raised
in ambush position. No movement whatsoever.
Basically got comfy and went to sleep.

periscoped about 5cm on one occasion. We didn't record data for 2nd 30s trial with (no sound), but he did way fewer head jerks and also changed direction and went away from speaker once sound ceased. We're convinced he can hear!
kept slightlyr raised (5cm head position the whole time.
21 tongue flicks in 2nd bonus 30s trial with no sound.
he was in a high degree of alertness whole time. Strange behaviour with head. Lots of very small movements left, right, up. Periscoped 3cm upward once.
so strange that he didn't tongue flick when moved head those few times.
36 tongue flicks and no other notable behaviours in 30s of no sound after first 30s trial. Much more relaxed during no-sound 30s.

Kept head raised ~4cm for whole trial. 8 tongue flicks in 2nd 30s trial (no sound). Throughout sound and defo at end of sound, he was flicking tongue heaps and right when the sound stopped, he stopped flicking tongue immediately.
periscoped in beginning for about 4cm briefly, but Chris reckons in response to hutch swaying.

35 tongue flicks during 2nd 30s trial. She froze whole time during sound, then only about 5s after sound stopped, she moved freely the rest of the no-sound trial. Clear differences in behaviour b/w sound vs no-sound trials.
always reorients in the hutch to face away from half wall.

1 parascoping too about 10cm during sound. 27 tongue flicks in 2nd 30s no-sound trial. Was heading toward sound during sound and when sound stopped, then u-bolted and went the other way and quicker. So approaching speaker slower (when sound on) than when bolting the other way without sound.
these hoplos pretty well seem to do the same thing every time: Go for a bit, then go back along their body.
Stayed in raised strike position (8cm off ground) whole trial. Hiss probs in response to box swaying at the start.
36 tongue flicks on no-sound trial after sound stopped. No obvious or apparent differences b/w two trials.
23 tongue flicks in 2nd 30s trial. He was frozen whole sound trial, then 5s into no sound he then started freely moving. Very obvious difference b/w two trials!
suddenly took off about 10s into trial. Makes you wonder if it took that long to register with her?
46 tongue flicks for 2nd trial (no-sound). No difference apparent b/w two trials.
when brought tail inwards toward body, she thought her tail hit another snake and she briefly waved her tail in randy receptiveness. LOL.
he didn't go asleep! Haha. Still didn't seem to take any notice or care about the sound. Or didn't hear it.
was already moving when sound started.
